{"title_page": "Turburea", "text_new": "{{about||the village in Arge\u0219 County|Corbeni|the village in V\u00e2lcea County|Gr\u0103di\u0219tea, V\u00e2lcea}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Gorj\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Gorj County\n|subdivisions           = Cocorova, Poiana, Spahii, \u0218ipotu, Turburea\n| name                    = Turburea\n| image_skyline           = \n| imagesize               = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| image_shield            = \n| shield_alt              = \n| image_map               = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|44|43|N|23|31|E|type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| established_date        = \n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 67.54\n| leader_party            = PSD\n| leader_name             = Ion B\u00e2rc\u0103<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-06 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| postal_code             = \n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Turburea''' is a commune in [[Gorj County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of five villages: Cocorova, Poiana, Spahii, \u0218ipotu and Turburea.\n\n[[Constantina Di\u021b\u0103-Tomescu]] was born there.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{GEOnet|-1173025}}\n\n{{Gorj County}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in Gorj County]]\n\n\n{{Gorj-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{about||the village in Arge\u0219 County|Corbeni|the village in V\u00e2lcea County|Gr\u0103di\u0219tea, V\u00e2lcea}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Gorj\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Gorj County\n|subdivisions           = Cocorova, Poiana, Spahii, \u0218ipotu, Turburea\n| name                    = Turburea\n| image_skyline           = \n| imagesize               = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| image_shield            = \n| shield_alt              = \n| image_map               = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|44|43|N|23|31|E|type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| established_date        = \n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 67.54\n| leader_party            = PDL\n| leader_name             = Barca Ion\n| postal_code             = \n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Turburea''' is a commune in [[Gorj County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of five villages: Cocorova, Poiana, Spahii, \u0218ipotu and Turburea.\n\n[[Constantina Di\u021b\u0103-Tomescu]] was born there.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{GEOnet|-1173025}}\n\n{{Gorj County}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in Gorj County]]\n\n\n{{Gorj-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turburea"}
{"title_page": "Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = Edgar Allan Poe House\n| nrhp_type = nhl\n| image = PoeHouse-Baltimore.jpg\n| caption = Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum in [[Baltimore, Maryland]]\n| location = [[Baltimore, Maryland]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|39|17|28.65|N|76|37|59.30|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = United States Baltimore#Maryland#USA\n| area =\n| built = 1830\n| architect =\n| architecture =\n| designated_nrhp_type = November 11, 1972<ref name=\"nhlsum\">{{cite web |url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1182&ResourceType=Building |title=Poe, Edgar Allan, House |accessdate=2009-03-30 |work=National Historic Landmark summary listing |publisher=National Park Service |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308085504/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1182&ResourceType=Building |archive-date=2009-03-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| added = November 11, 1972<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n| refnum = 71001043\n}}\n\nThe '''Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum''', located at 203 North Amity St. in [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], is the former home of American writer [[Edgar Allan Poe]] in the 1830s. The small unassuming structure, which was opened as a [[writer's house museum]] in 1949, is a typical [[Terraced house|row home]]. It was designated a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1972.<ref name=\"nhlsum\"/>\n\nDue to a loss of funding by the city of Baltimore, the Museum closed to the public in October 2012. [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore], the Museum's new governing body, reopened the Museum to the public on October 5, 2013.<ref name=\"articles.baltimoresun.com\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2013-10-05/entertainment/bs-hs-poe-house-20131005_1_poe-baltimore-edgar-allan-poe-house-baltimore-office|title=Edgar Allan Poe's house reopened to the public|work=Baltimore Sun|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe brick home, then numbered 3 Amity St.,<ref name=Silverman96>Silverman, Kenneth. ''Edgar A. Poe: Mournful and Never-ending Remembrance''. New York: Harper Perennial, 1991. p. 96. {{ISBN|0-06-092331-8}}</ref> and now numbered 203 North Amity Street, is assumed to have been built in 1830 and rented by Poe's aunt Maria Clemm in 1832. Clemm was joined in the home by her ailing mother, Elizabeth Cairnes Poe, and her daughter [[Virginia Eliza Clemm Poe|Virginia Clemm]]. Edgar Allan Poe moved in with the family in 1833<ref name=Silverman96/> around the age of 23, after leaving [[United States Military Academy|West Point]]. Virginia was 10 years old at the time; Poe would marry her three years later, though their only public ceremony was in 1836. Poe lived in the house from about 1833 to 1835.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/08/arts/edgar-allan-poe-house-in-baltimore-faces-closing.html|title=Fiscal Woe Haunting Baltimore Poe House|date=8 August 2011|work=The New York Times|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe house was rented using [[pension]] money that Elizabeth collected thanks to her husband, David Poe Sr., who was a veteran of the [[American Revolutionary War]]. The home is small and Poe's room on the top floor has a ceiling with a sharp pitch which is six feet high at its tallest point.<ref>Haas, Irvin. ''Historic Homes of American Authors''. Washington, DC: The Preservation Press, 1991. {{ISBN|0-89133-180-8}}. p. 78</ref>\n\nIn the 1930s, homes in the area, including Poe's, were set for demolition to make room for the \"Poe Homes\" [[public housing]] project.  The house was saved by the efforts of the [http://www.eapoe.org Edgar Allan Poe Society of Baltimore], which made arrangements with the city of Baltimore and opened the home as [http://www.eapoe.org/balt/poehse.htm The Baltimore Poe House] in 1949. \nFormer displays in the Museum included a lock of Poe's hair, a small piece of Poe's coffin, some original china that once belonged to John Allan (Poe's guardian after [[Eliza Poe]]'s death), and a large reproduction of the portrait of Virginia Clemm painted after her death as well as many other Poe-related images. An original 1849 [[obituary]] by Rufus Griswold in the October 24, 1849 edition of the ''Philadelphia Dollar Newspaper'' is also on display along with a reprint of Poe's original announcement for the creation of a new literary magazine to be called ''[[The Stylus]]'' &mdash; an endeavor that never came to fruition.\n\nThe Museum hosted a number of Poe events throughout the year. It claimed, for example, the largest Poe birthday celebration in the world held every January at the [[Westminster Hall and Burying Ground]], where Poe was buried following his death in October 1849. In 2009, the curator, Jeff Jerome, planned the biggest event of the Poe Bicentennial at Westminster Hall. He held a third funeral for Poe. Over 1,200 people attended two services. The event received national and international media attention and acclaim.\n\nIn 1979 during the house renovations, workers lifted the floorboards and found skeletal remains, reminiscent of Poe's story \"[[The Tell-Tale Heart]].\" These were found to be animal bones discarded into what is known as a \"trash pit\" or [[midden]] beneath the home.<ref>Gentile, Sal. \"[http://www.wboc.com/story/6844463/edgar-allan-poe-museum-staff-make-disturbing-find Edgar Allan Poe Museum staff make disturbing find],\" Associated Press. July 26, 2007.</ref>\n\nIn 2011, City of Baltimore officials reduced the Museum's subsidy, a decision that ultimately led to its closure in 2012. After the City cut off its $85,000 in annual support in 2011, the Museum was operating on reserve funds to the amount of $380,000 in the Poe House Fundraising account.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/08/arts/edgar-allan-poe-house-in-baltimore-faces-closing.html |work=The New York Times |first=Kate |last=Taylor |title=Edgar Allan Poe House in Baltimore Faces Closing |date=August 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nEfforts to secure the Museum's future came from such diverse places as: the non-profit project [http://penniesforpoe.com/ Pennies For Poe: Save the Poe House in Baltimore],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2011-10-06/entertainment/bs-ae-poe-fundraising-20111006_1_poe-fans-edgar-allan-poe-house-jeff-jerome|title=Plight of Baltimore's Poe House attracts worldwide attention|work=Baltimore Sun|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> the New York City based non-profit theatre company [http://www.bedlamensemble.org/press.php Bedlam Ensemble's] staging of ''The Delirium of Edgar Allan Poe'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://digitaljournal.com/article/313315|title='The Delirium of Edgar Allan Poe' to benefit Poe House and Museum (Includes interview)|work=digitaljournal.com|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> and the 2012 film [[The Raven (2012 film)|''The Raven'']].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/jacketcopy/2011/08/could-the-poe-movie-save-edgar-allan-poe-house-baltimore.html |work=Los Angeles Times |first=Carolyn |last=Kellogg |title=Could the Poe movie save Edgar Allan Poe's Baltimore house? |date=August 8, 2011}} [Author refers to the upcoming 2012 film ''The Raven'']</ref>\n\nJeff Jerome, the Museum's [[curator]] for more than three decades, was laid off in 2012. According to the Edgar Allan Poe Society of Baltimore, the Museum was closed on September 28, 2012 with no advance public notice, with plans to reorganize and reopen in 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eapoe.org/balt/poehse.htm |title=Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum |url-status=live |accessdate=2013-08-07}}</ref>\n\n==Poe Baltimore==\nIn 2013, a new non-profit organization, [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore], was established to serve as the Museum's new governing body and operate the Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum.\n\nPoe Baltimore's [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/mission-statement/ Mission Statement] includes that the organization \"...was created to fund, maintain and interpret The Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum, and to celebrate the legacy of one of Baltimore\u2019s most famous residents.  We are dedicated to maintaining the museum as a vibrant experience for the thousands of visitors who come from around the world each year, and as part of a broader mission of city-wide events and educational opportunities...\"\n\n[http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore] reopened the [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/museum/ Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum] to the public on October 5, 2013.<ref name=\"articles.baltimoresun.com\"/> [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore] is also working in conjunction with the Edgar Allan Poe Society of Baltimore.\n\n==Description==\nThe Poe House is a {{frac|2|1|2}} story two-bay brick structure with a gabled metal roof. The front door is on the left side of the west elevation, at the top of a wood stoop. The house is flanked on the north by a contiguous building; the south elevation is windowless. A single gabled [[dormer]] is centered in the west roof. To the rear a two-story ell projects from the south side of the main block. Its shed roof slopes to the north.<ref name=\"nrhpinv1\">{{cite web|url={{NHLS url|id=71001043}}|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory Nomination: Edgar Allan Poe House|last=Mendinghall|first=Joseph S.|author2=Preston, Edmund|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref> The house sits on the western edge of an active low-income housing project in the west Baltimore neighborhood of [[Poppleton, Baltimore|Poppleton]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/08/arts/edgar-allan-poe-house-in-baltimore-faces-closing.html?hp | work=The New York Times | first=Kate | last=Taylor | title=Edgar Allan Poe House in Baltimore Faces Closing | date=August 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.urbanitebaltimore.com/baltimore/picking-poppleton/Content?oid=1245686 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-08-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929234725/http://www.urbanitebaltimore.com/baltimore/picking-poppleton/Content?oid=1245686 |archive-date=2011-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe house is entered through the front living room, with a dining room to the rear and two steps down. From the dining room narrow stairs lead to the basement and the second floor. Two bedrooms occupy the second floor, and stairs lead to a small attic or garret, which may have been occupied by Poe. The house retains the majority of its original woodwork.<ref name=\"nrhpinv1\"/>\n\n==Works penned in this house==\nThough it cannot be fully proven, the Poe Society alleges that the following works were created while Poe was staying in this house:\n{|\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n\n'''Stories'''\n\n*''[[MS. Found in a Bottle]]''\n*''Lionizing: A Tale''\n*''Shadow-A Parable''\n*''[[Berenice (short story)|Berenice]]''\n*''[[Morella (short story)|Morella]]''\n*''[[King Pest|King Pest the First. A Tale containing an Allegory]]''\n*''[[The Unparalleled Adventure of One Hans Pfaall]]''\n| valign=\"top\" |\n\n'''Poems'''\n\n*\"[[Poems by Edgar Allan Poe#Hymn (1835)|Latin Hymn]]\"\n*\"[[Poems by Edgar Allan Poe#Enigma(1833)|Enigma]]\"\n*\"[[Poems by Edgar Allan Poe#Serenade (1833)|Serenade]]\"\n*\"[[Poems by Edgar Allan Poe#The Coliseum (1833)|The Coliseum]]\"\n|}\n\n==Poe House in popular culture==\nIn the opening scene of episode 2, season 3 \"[[All Due Respect (The Wire)|All Due Respect]],\" of the [[HBO]] series ''[[The Wire]]'', two low-level members of the [[Barksdale Organization|Barksdale Gang]] recall how one was once approached by a white tourist asking him if he knew the location of the \"Poe House\". Misunderstanding, he replies \"Look around, take your pick!\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/the-wire-1/all-due-respect-1/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113132949/http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/the-wire-1/all-due-respect-1/ |archive-date=2013-11-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''The Wire'' chronicles the activities of the fictional Barksdale Organization based in west Baltimore, where the Poe House is located.\n\nIn season 3 of the Telltale Games video game version of ''[[The Walking Dead (video game)|The Walking Dead]]'', one house in the Prescott camp is a visual homage to the Poe House.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe Museum (Richmond)|Edgar Allan Poe Museum]] in [[Richmond, Virginia]]\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe National Historic Site]] in [[Philadelphia]]\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe Cottage]] in the Bronx, New York\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum}}\n*[http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore]\n*[http://www.eapoe.org The Edgar Allan Poe Society of Baltimore]\n*[http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/travel/baltimore/index.htm  Baltimore, Maryland, a National Park Service ''Discover Our Shared Heritage'' Travel Itinerary]\n*[http://explore.baltimoreheritage.org/items/show/77?tour=12&index=12#.UlcUlijcGgw Explore Baltimore Heritage. Edgar Allan Poe House. By Ryan Artes, University of Baltimore]\n*[http://citylitproject.org/index.cfm?page=news&newsid=138 Poe House: Landmark Returns with a \"Poe\"-pen House. Oct. 3, 2013]\n*{{MHT url|id=79|title=Edgar Allan Poe House. National Register Listings in Maryland}}\n*[https://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&hl=en&geocode=&q=poe+house,+Baltimore,+Maryland&sll=39.288459,-76.604211&sspn=0.007673,0.014763&ie=UTF8&ll=39.291299,-76.633201&spn=0,359.985237&z=16&layer=c&cbll=39.291379,-76.633209&panoid=vbq2Zy8XHGPZRZZi_VFDHQ&cbp=12,82.29920761890918,,0,-3.360449030098446  Poe House on Google Street View]\n\n{{Edgar Allan Poe|state=expanded}}\n{{Maryland museums|state=collapsed}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Maryland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poe, Edgar Allan, House And Museum}}\n[[Category:Biographical museums in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Edgar Allan Poe]]\n[[Category:Historic house museums in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1830]]\n[[Category:Houses in Baltimore]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Baltimore]]\n[[Category:Literary museums in the United States]]\n[[Category:Museums in Baltimore]]\n[[Category:National Historic Landmarks in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Poppleton, Baltimore]]\n[[Category:1830 establishments in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Museums established in 1949]]\n[[Category:Homes of American writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = Edgar Allan Poe House\n| nrhp_type = nhl\n| image = PoeHouse-Baltimore.jpg\n| caption = Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum in [[Baltimore, Maryland]]\n| location = [[Baltimore, Maryland]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|39|17|28.65|N|76|37|59.30|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = United States Baltimore#Maryland#USA\n| area =\n| built = 1830\n| architect =\n| architecture =\n| designated_nrhp_type = November 11, 1972<ref name=\"nhlsum\">{{cite web |url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1182&ResourceType=Building |title=Poe, Edgar Allan, House |accessdate=2009-03-30 |work=National Historic Landmark summary listing |publisher=National Park Service |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308085504/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1182&ResourceType=Building |archive-date=2009-03-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| added = November 11, 1972<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n| refnum = 71001043\n}}\n\nThe '''Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum''', located at 203 North Amity St. in [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], is the former home of American writer [[Edgar Allan Poe]] in the 1830s. The small unassuming structure, which was opened as a [[writer's house museum]] in 1949, is a typical [[Terraced house|row home]]. It was designated a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1972.<ref name=\"nhlsum\"/>\n\nDue to a loss of funding by the city of Baltimore, the Museum closed to the public in October 2012. [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore], the Museum's new governing body, reopened the Museum to the public on October 5, 2013.<ref name=\"articles.baltimoresun.com\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2013-10-05/entertainment/bs-hs-poe-house-20131005_1_poe-baltimore-edgar-allan-poe-house-baltimore-office|title=Edgar Allan Poe's house reopened to the public|work=Baltimore Sun|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe brick home, then numbered 3 Amity St.,<ref name=Silverman96>Silverman, Kenneth. ''Edgar A. Poe: Mournful and Never-ending Remembrance''. New York: Harper Perennial, 1991. p. 96. {{ISBN|0-06-092331-8}}</ref> and now numbered 203 North Amity Street, is assumed to have been built in 1830 and rented by Poe's aunt Maria Clemm in 1832. Clemm was joined in the home by her ailing mother, Elizabeth Cairnes Poe, and her daughter [[Virginia Eliza Clemm Poe|Virginia Clemm]]. Edgar Allan Poe moved in with the family in 1833<ref name=Silverman96/> around the age of 23, after leaving [[United States Military Academy|West Point]]. Virginia was 10 years old at the time; Poe would marry her three years later, though their only public ceremony was in 1836. Poe lived in the house from about 1833 to 1835.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/08/arts/edgar-allan-poe-house-in-baltimore-faces-closing.html|title=Fiscal Woe Haunting Baltimore Poe House|date=8 August 2011|work=The New York Times|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe house was rented using [[pension]] money that Elizabeth collected thanks to her husband, David Poe Sr., who was a veteran of the [[American Revolutionary War]]. The home is small and Poe's room on the top floor has a ceiling with a sharp pitch which is six feet high at its tallest point.<ref>Haas, Irvin. ''Historic Homes of American Authors''. Washington, DC: The Preservation Press, 1991. {{ISBN|0-89133-180-8}}. p. 78</ref>\n\nIn the 1930s, homes in the area, including Poe's, were set for demolition to make room for the \"Poe Homes\" [[public housing]] project.  The house was saved by the efforts of the [http://www.eapoe.org Edgar Allan Poe Society of Baltimore], which made arrangements with the city of Baltimore and opened the home as [http://www.eapoe.org/balt/poehse.htm The Baltimore Poe House] in 1949. \nFormer displays in the Museum included a lock of Poe's hair, a small piece of Poe's coffin, some original china that once belonged to John Allan (Poe's guardian after [[Eliza Poe]]'s death), and a large reproduction of the portrait of Virginia Clemm painted after her death as well as many other Poe-related images. An original 1849 [[obituary]] by Rufus Griswold in the October 24, 1849 edition of the ''Philadelphia Dollar Newspaper'' is also on display along with a reprint of Poe's original announcement for the creation of a new literary magazine to be called ''[[The Stylus]]'' &mdash; an endeavor that never came to fruition.\n\nThe Museum hosted a number of Poe events throughout the year. It claimed, for example, the largest Poe birthday celebration in the world held every January at the [[Westminster Hall and Burying Ground]], where Poe was buried following his death in October 1849. In 2009, the curator, Jeff Jerome, planned the biggest event of the Poe Bicentennial at Westminster Hall. He held a third funeral for Poe. Over 1,200 people attended two services. The event received national and international media attention and acclaim.\n\nIn 1979 during the house renovations, workers lifted the floorboards and found skeletal remains, reminiscent of Poe's story \"[[The Tell-Tale Heart]].\" These were found to be animal bones discarded into what is known as a \"trash pit\" or [[midden]] beneath the home.<ref>Gentile, Sal. \"[http://www.wboc.com/story/6844463/edgar-allan-poe-museum-staff-make-disturbing-find Edgar Allan Poe Museum staff make disturbing find],\" Associated Press. July 26, 2007.</ref>\n\nIn 2011, City of Baltimore officials reduced the Museum's subsidy, a decision that ultimately led to its closure in 2012. After the City cut off its $85,000 in annual support in 2011, the Museum was operating on reserve funds to the amount of $380,000 in the Poe House Fundraising account.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/08/arts/edgar-allan-poe-house-in-baltimore-faces-closing.html |work=The New York Times |first=Kate |last=Taylor |title=Edgar Allan Poe House in Baltimore Faces Closing |date=August 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nEfforts to secure the Museum's future came from such diverse places as: the non-profit project [http://penniesforpoe.com/ Pennies For Poe: Save the Poe House in Baltimore],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2011-10-06/entertainment/bs-ae-poe-fundraising-20111006_1_poe-fans-edgar-allan-poe-house-jeff-jerome|title=Plight of Baltimore's Poe House attracts worldwide attention|work=Baltimore Sun|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> the New York City based non-profit theatre company [http://www.bedlamensemble.org/press.php Bedlam Ensemble's] staging of ''The Delirium of Edgar Allan Poe'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://digitaljournal.com/article/313315|title='The Delirium of Edgar Allan Poe' to benefit Poe House and Museum (Includes interview)|work=digitaljournal.com|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> and the 2012 film [[The Raven (2012 film)|''The Raven'']].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/jacketcopy/2011/08/could-the-poe-movie-save-edgar-allan-poe-house-baltimore.html |work=Los Angeles Times |first=Carolyn |last=Kellogg |title=Could the Poe movie save Edgar Allan Poe's Baltimore house? |date=August 8, 2011}} [Author refers to the upcoming 2012 film ''The Raven'']</ref>\n\nJeff Jerome, the Museum's [[curator]] for more than three decades, was laid off in 2012. According to the Edgar Allan Poe Society of Baltimore, the Museum was closed on September 28, 2012 with no advance public notice, with plans to reorganize and reopen in 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eapoe.org/balt/poehse.htm |title=Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum |url-status=live |accessdate=2013-08-07}}</ref>\n\n==Poe Baltimore==\nIn 2013, a new non-profit organization, [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore], was established to serve as the Museum's new governing body and operate the Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum.\n\nPoe Baltimore's [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/mission-statement/ Mission Statement] includes that the organization \"...was created to fund, maintain and interpret The Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum, and to celebrate the legacy of one of Baltimore\u2019s most famous residents.  We are dedicated to maintaining the museum as a vibrant experience for the thousands of visitors who come from around the world each year, and as part of a broader mission of city-wide events and educational opportunities...\"\n\n[http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore] reopened the [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/museum/ Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum] to the public on October 5, 2013.<ref name=\"articles.baltimoresun.com\"/> [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore] is also working in conjunction with the Edgar Allan Poe Society of Baltimore.\n\n==Description==\nThe Poe House is a {{frac|2|1|2}} story two-bay brick structure with a gabled metal roof. The front door is on the left side of the west elevation, at the top of a wood stoop. The house is flanked on the north by a contiguous building; the south elevation is windowless. A single gabled [[dormer]] is centered in the west roof. To the rear a two-story ell projects from the south side of the main block. Its shed roof slopes to the north.<ref name=\"nrhpinv1\">{{cite web|url={{NHLS url|id=71001043}}|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory Nomination: Edgar Allan Poe House|last=Mendinghall|first=Joseph S.|author2=Preston, Edmund|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref> The house sits on the western edge of an active low-income housing project in the west Baltimore neighborhood of [[Poppleton, Baltimore|Poppleton]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/08/arts/edgar-allan-poe-house-in-baltimore-faces-closing.html?hp | work=The New York Times | first=Kate | last=Taylor | title=Edgar Allan Poe House in Baltimore Faces Closing | date=August 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.urbanitebaltimore.com/baltimore/picking-poppleton/Content?oid=1245686 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-08-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929234725/http://www.urbanitebaltimore.com/baltimore/picking-poppleton/Content?oid=1245686 |archive-date=2011-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe house is entered through the front living room, with a dining room to the rear and two steps down. From the dining room narrow stairs lead to the basement and the second floor. Two bedrooms occupy the second floor, and stairs lead to a small attic or garret, which may have been occupied by Poe. The house retains the majority of its original woodwork.<ref name=\"nrhpinv1\"/>\n\n==Works penned in this house==\nThough it cannot be fully proven, the Poe Society alleges that the following works were created while Poe was staying in this house:\n{|\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n\n'''Stories'''\n\n*''[[MS. Found in a Bottle]]''\n*''Lionizing: A Tale''\n*''Shadow-A Parable''\n*''[[Berenice (short story)|Berenice]]''\n*''[[Morella (short story)|Morella]]''\n*''[[King Pest|King Pest the First. A Tale containing an Allegory]]''\n*''[[The Unparalleled Adventure of One Hans Pfaall]]''\n| valign=\"top\" |\n\n'''Poems'''\n\n*\"[[Poems by Edgar Allan Poe#Hymn (1835)|Latin Hymn]]\"\n*\"[[Poems by Edgar Allan Poe#Enigma(1833)|Enigma]]\"\n*\"[[Poems by Edgar Allan Poe#Serenade (1833)|Serenade]]\"\n*\"[[Poems by Edgar Allan Poe#The Coliseum (1833)|The Coliseum]]\"\n|}\n\n==Poe House in popular culture==\nIn the opening scene of episode 2, season 3 \"[[All Due Respect (The Wire)|All Due Respect]],\" of the [[HBO]] series ''[[The Wire]]'', two low-level members of the [[Barksdale Organization|Barksdale Gang]] recall how one was once approached by a white tourist asking him if he knew the location of the \"Poe House\". Misunderstanding, he replies \"Look around, take your pick!\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/the-wire-1/all-due-respect-1/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113132949/http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/the-wire-1/all-due-respect-1/ |archive-date=2013-11-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''The Wire'' chronicles the activities of the fictional Barksdale Organization based in west Baltimore, where the Poe House is located.\n\nIn season 3 of the Telltale Games video game version of ''[[The Walking Dead (video game)|The Walking Dead]]'', one house in the Prescott camp is a visual homage to the Poe House.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe Museum (Richmond)|Edgar Allan Poe Museum]] in [[Richmond, Virginia]]\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe National Historic Site]] in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe Cottage]] in The Bronx, New York\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum}}\n*[http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore]\n*[http://www.eapoe.org The Edgar Allan Poe Society of Baltimore]\n*[http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/travel/baltimore/index.htm  Baltimore, Maryland, a National Park Service ''Discover Our Shared Heritage'' Travel Itinerary]\n*[http://explore.baltimoreheritage.org/items/show/77?tour=12&index=12#.UlcUlijcGgw Explore Baltimore Heritage. Edgar Allan Poe House. By Ryan Artes, University of Baltimore]\n*[http://citylitproject.org/index.cfm?page=news&newsid=138 Poe House: Landmark Returns with a \"Poe\"-pen House. Oct. 3, 2013]\n*{{MHT url|id=79|title=Edgar Allan Poe House. National Register Listings in Maryland}}\n*[https://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&hl=en&geocode=&q=poe+house,+Baltimore,+Maryland&sll=39.288459,-76.604211&sspn=0.007673,0.014763&ie=UTF8&ll=39.291299,-76.633201&spn=0,359.985237&z=16&layer=c&cbll=39.291379,-76.633209&panoid=vbq2Zy8XHGPZRZZi_VFDHQ&cbp=12,82.29920761890918,,0,-3.360449030098446  Poe House on Google Street View]\n\n{{Edgar Allan Poe|state=expanded}}\n{{Maryland museums|state=collapsed}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Maryland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poe, Edgar Allan, House And Museum}}\n[[Category:Biographical museums in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Edgar Allan Poe]]\n[[Category:Historic house museums in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1830]]\n[[Category:Houses in Baltimore]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Baltimore]]\n[[Category:Literary museums in the United States]]\n[[Category:Museums in Baltimore]]\n[[Category:National Historic Landmarks in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Poppleton, Baltimore]]\n[[Category:1830 establishments in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Museums established in 1949]]\n[[Category:Homes of American writers]]\n", "name_user": "Station1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edgar_Allan_Poe_House_and_Museum"}
{"title_page": "Error", "text_new": "{{short description|Deviation from what is correct}}\n{{Others}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{confusing|date=July 2011}}\n{{unfocused|date=April 2018}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2019}}\n}}\nAn '''error''' (from the Latin ''error'', meaning \"wandering\")<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thesaurus.com/browse/error|title=Word Origin & History|first=|last=|date=|website=|publisher=[[Thesaurus]]|language=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=June 10, 2018}}</ref> is an action which is inaccurate or incorrect.<ref>{{cite dictionary|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/error|title=Definition of Error|dictionary=[[Dictionary.com|Dictionary]]|access-date=June 10, 2018}}</ref> In some usages, an error is synonymous with a '''mistake'''. In statistics, \"error\" refers to the difference between the value which has been computed and the correct value.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abs.gov.au/websitedbs/a3121120.nsf/home/statistical+language+-+types+of+error|title=Statistical Language - Types of Error|first=|last=|date=|website=|publisher=[[Australian Bureau of Statistics]]|language=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=June 10, 2018}}</ref> An error could result in [[failure]] or in a deviation from the intended performance or behaviour.<ref>{{Cite book|title=European Committee for Electrotechnical Standardization (CENELEC) - EN 50128|last=|first=|publisher=CENELEC|year=2011|ISSN=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Human behavior==\nOne reference differentiates between \"error\" and \"mistake\" as follows:\n{{quote|An 'error' is a deviation from accuracy or correctness. A 'mistake' is an error caused by a fault: the fault being misjudgment, carelessness, or forgetfulness. Now, say that I run a stop sign because I was in a hurry, and wasn't concentrating, and the police stop me, that is a mistake. If, however, I try to park in an area with conflicting signs, and I get a ticket because I was incorrect on my interpretation of what the signs meant, that would be an error. The first time it would be an error. The second time it would be a mistake since I should have known better.<ref>Robinson, P. \"In the Matter of:The Gatekeeper: The Gate Contracts\"</ref>}}\n\nIn [[human behavior]] the norms or expectations for behavior or its consequences can be derived from the intention of the actor or from the expectations of other individuals or from a social grouping or from [[social norms]]. (See [[deviance (sociology)|deviance]].) Gaffes and faux pas can be labels for certain instances of this kind of error. More serious departures from social norms carry labels such as misbehavior and labels from the legal system, such as [[misdemeanor]] and [[crime]]. Departures from norms connected to religion can have other labels, such as [[sin]].\n\nAn individual [[language]] user's deviations from standard language norms in [[grammar]], [[pronunciation]] and [[orthography]] are sometimes referred to as [[Error (linguistics)|errors]]. However, in light of the role of language usage in everyday [[social class]] distinctions, many feel that [[linguistics]] should restrain itself from such [[linguistic prescription|prescriptivist judgments]] to avoid reinforcing dominant class value claims about what linguistic forms should and should not be used. One may distinguish various kinds of linguistic errors<ref>''[http://www.stanford.edu/~zwicky/mistakes.pdf Mistakes],'' [[Arnold Zwicky]], 1980, Advocate Publishing Group, {{oclc|8468508}} The ISBN printed in the document (0-89894-030-5) is invalid, causing a checksum error</ref> \u2013 some, such as [[aphasia]] or [[speech disorder]]s, where the user is unable to say what they intend to, are generally considered errors, while cases where natural, intended speech is [[nonstandard dialect|non-standard]] (as in vernacular dialects), are considered legitimate speech in scholarly linguistics, but might be considered errors in prescriptivist contexts. See also [[Error analysis (linguistics)]].\n\n[[Image:PrintingError.jpg|thumb|480px|[[Herzliya Airport]] (Israel) [[runway]] location and [[Airfield traffic pattern|traffic pattern]] chart (left) was erroneously printed as a result of \"black layer\" 180\u00b0 misplacement. The corrected chart is on the right.    (Note north is to the right on both charts.)]]\n[[Image:Judas Bible2.jpg|thumb|240px|The [[ Bible errata #King James |'Judas' Bible]] in St Mary's Church, [[Totnes]], [[Devon]].    In this edition 'Judas' appears instead of 'Jesus' in Matthew 26:36.    This copy has the misprint corrected by a slip of paper pasted over it.<ref>According to a note in St Mary's Church, Totnes, Cornwall, UK</ref>]]\n\n=== Gaffe {{Anchor|Gaff}} ===<!-- This section is linked from (the Dab) [[Gaff]]. It was noted here, from 09:24, 29 June 2007 to 24 May 2008, as linked from [[Spoonerism]], but the link in that article has been removed (probably wisely) -->\n{{see also|Microphone gaffe|Political gaffe|Howler (error)}}\nA '''gaffe''' is usually made in a [[social environment]] and may come from saying something that may be true but inappropriate. It may also be an erroneous attempt to reveal a truth. Gaffes can be [[malapropism]]s, grammatical errors or other verbal and gestural weaknesses or revelations through [[body language]]. Actually revealing factual or social truth through words or body language, however, can commonly result in embarrassment or, when the gaffe has negative connotations, friction between people involved.\n\nPhilosophers and psychologists interested in the nature of the gaffe include [[Sigmund Freud]] ([[Freudian slip]]) and [[Gilles Deleuze]]. Deleuze, in his ''[[The Logic of Sense]]'', places the gaffe in a developmental process that can culminate in stuttering.\n\nSports writers and journalists commonly use \"gaffe\" to refer to any kind of mistake, e.g., a dropped ball ([[baseball error]]) by a player in a baseball game.\n\n==Science and engineering==\n[[File:TrafficSignIsraelError.JPG|thumb|left|180px|Erroneous traffic sign in [[Israel]]. The correct sign is depicted on the lower-right corner.]]\n{{See also|Observational error|Bias (statistics)|Measurement uncertainty}}\n\nIn [[statistics]], an [[errors and residuals|''error'' (or ''residual'')]] is not a \"mistake\" but rather a difference between a computed, estimated, or measured value and the accepted true, specified, or theoretically correct value.\n\nIn science and engineering in general, an error is defined as a difference between the desired and actual [[Performance (disambiguation)|performance]] or [[behavior]] of a [[system]] or [[Object (philosophy)|object]]. This definition is the basis of operation for many types of [[control system]]s, in which error is defined as the difference between a set point and the process value. An example of this would be the thermostat in a home heating system\u2014the operation of the heating equipment is controlled by the difference (the error) between the thermostat setting and the sensed air temperature. Another approach is related to considering a scientific hypothesis as true or false, giving birth to two types of errors: [[Type I and type II errors|Type 1 and Type 2]]. The first one is when a true hypothesis is considered false, while the second is the reverse (a false one is considered true).\n\n[[Engineer]]s seek to design [[gadget|devices]], [[machine]]s and [[system]]s and in such a way as to mitigate or preferably avoid the effects of error, whether [[Hanlon's Razor|unintentional or not]]. Such errors in a system can be latent [[design]] errors that may go unnoticed for years, until the right set of circumstances arises that cause them to become active. Other errors in engineered systems can arise due to [[human error]], which includes [[cognitive bias]]. [[Human factors]] engineering is often applied to designs in an attempt to minimize this type of error by making systems more forgiving or [[error-tolerant]].\n\n(In [[computational mechanics]], when solving a system such as ''Ax''&nbsp;=&nbsp;''b'' there is a distinction between the \"error\" \u2014 the inaccuracy in ''x'' \u2014 and [[Residual (numerical analysis)|residual]]\u2014the inaccuracy in ''Ax''.)\n\n==Numerical analysis==\n{{main| Approximation error}}\n[[Numerical analysis]] provides a variety of techniques to represent (store) and compute [[approximation]]s to mathematical numerical values. Errors arise from a trade-off between efficiency (space and computation time) and precision, which is limited anyway, since (using common [[floating-point arithmetic]]) only a finite amount of values can be represented exactly. The discrepancy between the exact mathematical value and the stored/computed value is called the [[approximation error]].\n\n==Cybernetics==\nThe word ''[[cybernetics]]'' stems from the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] [[w:el:\u039a\u03c5\u03b2\u03b5\u03c1\u03bd\u03ae\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2|\u039a\u03c5\u03b2\u03b5\u03c1\u03bd\u03ae\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2]] (''kybern\u0113t\u0113s'', steersman, governor, pilot, or rudder \u2014 the same root as [[government]]). In applying corrections to the trajectory or course being steered cybernetics can be seen as the most general approach to error and its correction for the achievement of any goal. The term was suggested by [[Norbert Wiener]] to describe a new science of control and information in the animal and the machine. Wiener's early work was on [[noise]].\n\nThe cybernetician [[Gordon Pask]] held that the error that drives a [[servomechanism]] can be seen as a difference between a pair of analogous concepts in a servomechanism: the current state and the goal state. Later he suggested error can also be seen as an innovation or a contradiction depending on the context and perspective of interacting (observer) participants. The founder of [[management cybernetics]], \n[[Stafford Beer]], applied these ideas most notably in his [[viable system model]].\n\n==Biology==\n{{main|mutation}}\nIn [[biology]], an ''error'' is said to occur when perfect fidelity is lost in the copying of [[information]]. For example, in an asexually reproducing species, an error (or mutation) has occurred for each [[DNA]] [[nucleotide]] that differs between the [[child]] and the [[parent]]. Many of these mutations can be harmful, but unlike other types of errors, some are neutral or even beneficial. Mutations are an important force driving [[evolution]]. Mutations that make organisms more adapted to their [[environment (biophysical)|environment]] increase in the population through [[natural selection]] as organisms with favorable mutations have more [[offspring]].\n\n==Philately==\nIn [[philately]], an ''error'' refers to a [[postage stamp]] or piece of [[postal stationery]] that exhibits a printing or production mistake that differentiates it from a normal specimen or from the intended result. Examples are stamps printed in the wrong color or missing one or more colors, printed with a vignette [[Inverted Jenny|inverted]] in relation to its frame, produced without any perforations on one or more sides when the normal stamps are perforated, or printed on the wrong type of paper. Legitimate errors must always be produced and sold unintentionally. Such errors may or may not be scarce or rare. A ''[[Postage stamp design error|design error]]'' may refer to a mistake in the design of the stamp, such as a mislabeled subject, even if there are no printing or production mistakes.\n\n==Law==\n{{main|Error (law)}}\nIn [[Appeal|appellate review]], error typically refers to mistakes made by a [[trial court]] or some other court of first instance in applying the law in a particular [[legal case]].  This may involve such mistakes as improper admission of [[Evidence (law)|evidence]], inappropriate [[Jury instruction|instructions]] to the [[jury]], or applying the wrong [[Legal burden of proof|standard of proof]].\n\n== Stock market ==\n{{Main article|Fat-finger error}}\nA stock market error is a stock market transaction that was done due to an error, due to human [[failure]] or [[computer error]]s.\n\n==Governmental policy==\nWithin United States government intelligence agencies, such as [[Central Intelligence Agency]] agencies, ''error'' refers to ''intelligence error'', as previous assumptions that used to exist at a senior intelligence level within senior intelligence agencies, but has since been disproven, and is sometimes eventually listed as unclassified, and therefore more available to the [[General public|public]] and [[citizenry]] of the United States. The [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of information act]] provides American citizenry with a means to read intelligence reports that were mired in error. Per United States Central Intelligence Agency's website (as of August, 2008) intelligence error is described as:\n\n\"Intelligence errors are factual inaccuracies in analysis resulting from poor or missing data; intelligence failure is systemic organizational surprise resulting from incorrect, missing, discarded, or inadequate hypotheses.\"<ref>United States Central Intelligence Agency. [https://www.cia.gov/library/center-for-the-study-of-intelligence/csi-publications/books-and-monographs/analytic-culture-in-the-u-s-intelligence-community/chapter_1.htm Analytic Culture in the U.S. Intelligence Community]. Retrieved August 30, 2008.</ref>\n\n==Numismatics==\nIn [[numismatics]], an ''error'' refers to a [[coin]] or [[medal]] that has a minting mistake, similar to errors found in philately. Because the U.S. [[Mint (coin)|Bureau of the Mint]] keeps a careful eye on all potential errors, errors on U.S. coins are very few and usually very scarce. Examples of numismatic errors: extra metal attached to a coin, a clipped coin caused by the coin stamp machine stamping a second coin too early, double stamping of a coin. A coin that has been overdated, e.g.: 1942/41, is also considered an error.\n\n==See also==\n{{too many see alsos|date=June 2019}}\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Blooper]]\n* [[Blunder (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Error analysis (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Perfection]]\n* [[Popular errors]]\n* [[Refractive error]]\n* [[Trial and error]]\n* [[Margin of error]]\n* [[Medical error]]\n\n'''Psychology of error'''\n* [[Absent-mindedness]]\n* [[Lapsus]]\n\n'''Error in reasoning'''\n* [[Fallacy]]\n**[[Informal fallacy]]\n**[[Formal fallacy]]\n\n'''[[Error (linguistics)|Errors in language]]'''\n*[[Chinglish]]\n*[[Clerical error]]\n* [[Speech error]]\n* [[Typographical error]]\n*[[barbarism (linguistics)|Barbarism]]\n*[[Solecism]]\n\n'''Errors in science, technology'''\n* [[Custom error page]]\n* [[Divide by zero]]\n* [[Mathematical fallacy]]\n* [[Infinite loop]]\n* [[Stack overflow]]\n* [[Software bug]]\n\n'''Error diagnosis, correction and prevention'''\n* [[Error-correcting code memory]]\n* [[Error detection and correction]]\n* [[Error Detection and Handling]]\n* [[Forensic engineering]]\n* [[Root cause]]\n* [[Root cause analysis]]\n* [[Spell checking]]\n* [[Swiss cheese model]] of accident causation in human systems\n\n'''Production quality terminology'''\n* [[Nonconformity (quality)|Nonconformity]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{wiktionary}}[https://techno-ahmad.blogspot.com/2020/04/5-errors-Natural-Referencing.html 5 Classic Errors in the Website for Natural Reference]\n\n* [http://www.accuracyproject.org/cbe-errors-books.html Errors contained in reference books \u2013 Internet Accuracy Project]\n\n[[Category:Error| ]]\n[[Category:Human communication]]\n[[Category:Measurement]]\n\n[[es:Error]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Deviation from what is correct}}\n{{Others}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{confusing|date=July 2011}}\n{{unfocused|date=April 2018}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2019}}\n}}\nAn '''error''' (from the Latin ''error'', meaning \"wandering\")<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thesaurus.com/browse/error|title=Word Origin & History|first=|last=|date=|website=|publisher=[[Thesaurus]]|language=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=June 10, 2018}}</ref> is an action which is inaccurate or incorrect.<ref>{{cite dictionary|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/error|title=Definition of Error|dictionary=[[Dictionary.com|Dictionary]]|access-date=June 10, 2018}}</ref> In some usages, an error is synonymous with a '''mistake'''. In statistics, \"error\" refers to the difference between the value which has been computed and the correct value.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abs.gov.au/websitedbs/a3121120.nsf/home/statistical+language+-+types+of+error|title=Statistical Language - Types of Error|first=|last=|date=|website=|publisher=[[Australian Bureau of Statistics]]|language=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=June 10, 2018}}</ref> An error could result in [[failure]] or in a deviation from the intended performance or behaviour.<ref>{{Cite book|title=European Committee for Electrotechnical Standardization (CENELEC) - EN 50128|last=|first=|publisher=CENELEC|year=2011|ISSN=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Human behavior==\nOne reference differentiates between \"error\" and \"mistake\" as follows:\n{{quote|An 'error' is a deviation from accuracy or correctness. A 'mistake' is an error caused by a fault: the fault being misjudgment, carelessness, or forgetfulness. Now, say that I run a stop sign because I was in a hurry, and wasn't concentrating, and the police stop me, that is a mistake. If, however, I try to park in an area with conflicting signs, and I get a ticket because I was incorrect on my interpretation of what the signs meant, that would be an error. The first time it would be an error. The second time it would be a mistake since I should have known better.<ref>Robinson, P. \"In the Matter of:The Gatekeeper: The Gate Contracts\"</ref>}}\n\nIn [[human behavior]] the norms or expectations for behavior or its consequences can be derived from the intention of the actor or from the expectations of other individuals or from a social grouping or from [[social norms]]. (See [[deviance (sociology)|deviance]].) Gaffes and faux pas can be labels for certain instances of this kind of error. More serious departures from social norms carry labels such as misbehavior and labels from the legal system, such as [[misdemeanor]] and [[crime]]. Departures from norms connected to religion can have other labels, such as [[sin]].\n\nAn individual [[language]] user's deviations from standard language norms in [[grammar]], [[pronunciation]] and [[orthography]] are sometimes referred to as [[Error (linguistics)|errors]]. However, in light of the role of language usage in everyday [[social class]] distinctions, many feel that [[linguistics]] should restrain itself from such [[linguistic prescription|prescriptivist judgments]] to avoid reinforcing dominant class value claims about what linguistic forms should and should not be used. One may distinguish various kinds of linguistic errors<ref>''[http://www.stanford.edu/~zwicky/mistakes.pdf Mistakes],'' [[Arnold Zwicky]], 1980, Advocate Publishing Group, {{oclc|8468508}} The ISBN printed in the document (0-89894-030-5) is invalid, causing a checksum error</ref> \u2013 some, such as [[aphasia]] or [[speech disorder]]s, where the user is unable to say what they intend to, are generally considered errors, while cases where natural, intended speech is [[nonstandard dialect|non-standard]] (as in vernacular dialects), are considered legitimate speech in scholarly linguistics, but might be considered errors in prescriptivist contexts. See also [[Error analysis (linguistics)]].\n\n[[Image:PrintingError.jpg|thumb|480px|[[Herzliya Airport]] (Israel) [[runway]] location and [[Airfield traffic pattern|traffic pattern]] chart (left) was erroneously printed as a result of \"black layer\" 180\u00b0 misplacement. The corrected chart is on the right.    (Note north is to the right on both charts.)]]\n[[Image:Judas Bible2.jpg|thumb|240px|The [[ Bible errata #King James |'Judas' Bible]] in St Mary's Church, [[Totnes]], [[Devon]].    In this edition 'Judas' appears instead of 'Jesus' in Matthew 26:36.    This copy has the misprint corrected by a slip of paper pasted over it.<ref>According to a note in St Mary's Church, Totnes, Cornwall, UK</ref>]]\n\n=== Gaffe {{Anchor|Gaff}} ===<!-- This section is linked from (the Dab) [[Gaff]]. It was noted here, from 09:24, 29 June 2007 to 24 May 2008, as linked from [[Spoonerism]], but the link in that article has been removed (probably wisely) -->\n{{see also|Microphone gaffe|Political gaffe|Howler (error)}}\nA '''gaffe''' is usually made in a [[social environment]] and may come from saying something that may be true but inappropriate. It may also be an erroneous attempt to reveal a truth. Gaffes can be [[malapropism]]s, grammatical errors or other verbal and gestural weaknesses or revelations through [[body language]]. Actually revealing factual or social truth through words or body language, however, can commonly result in embarrassment or, when the gaffe has negative connotations, friction between people involved.\n\nPhilosophers and psychologists interested in the nature of the gaffe include [[Sigmund Freud]] ([[Freudian slip]]) and [[Gilles Deleuze]]. Deleuze, in his ''[[The Logic of Sense]]'', places the gaffe in a developmental process that can culminate in stuttering.\n\nSports writers and journalists commonly use \"gaffe\" to refer to any kind of mistake, e.g., a dropped ball ([[baseball error]]) by a player in a baseball game.\n\n==Science and engineering==\n[[File:TrafficSignIsraelError.JPG|thumb|left|180px|Erroneous traffic sign in [[Israel]]. The correct sign is depicted on the lower-right corner.]]\n{{See also|Observational error|Bias (statistics)|Measurement uncertainty}}\n\nIn [[statistics]], an [[errors and residuals|''error'' (or ''residual'')]] is not a \"mistake\" but rather a difference between a computed, estimated, or measured value and the accepted true, specified, or theoretically correct value.\n\nIn science and engineering in general, an error is defined as a difference between the desired and actual [[Performance (disambiguation)|performance]] or [[behavior]] of a [[system]] or [[Object (philosophy)|object]]. This definition is the basis of operation for many types of [[control system]]s, in which error is defined as the difference between a set point and the process value. An example of this would be the thermostat in a home heating system\u2014the operation of the heating equipment is controlled by the difference (the error) between the thermostat setting and the sensed air temperature. Another approach is related to considering a scientific hypothesis as true or false, giving birth to two types of errors: [[Type I and type II errors|Type 1 and Type 2]]. The first one is when a true hypothesis is considered false, while the second is the reverse (a false one is considered true).\n\n[[Engineer]]s seek to design [[gadget|devices]], [[machine]]s and [[system]]s and in such a way as to mitigate or preferably avoid the effects of error, whether [[Hanlon's Razor|unintentional or not]]. Such errors in a system can be latent [[design]] errors that may go unnoticed for years, until the right set of circumstances arises that cause them to become active. Other errors in engineered systems can arise due to [[human error]], which includes [[cognitive bias]]. [[Human factors]] engineering is often applied to designs in an attempt to minimize this type of error by making systems more forgiving or [[error-tolerant]].\n\n(In [[computational mechanics]], when solving a system such as ''Ax''&nbsp;=&nbsp;''b'' there is a distinction between the \"error\" \u2014 the inaccuracy in ''x'' \u2014 and [[Residual (numerical analysis)|residual]]\u2014the inaccuracy in ''Ax''.)\n\n==Numerical analysis==\n{{main| Approximation error}}\n[[Numerical analysis]] provides a variety of techniques to represent (store) and compute [[approximation]]s to mathematical numerical values. Errors arise from a trade-off between efficiency (space and computation time) and precision, which is limited anyway, since (using common [[floating-point arithmetic]]) only a finite amount of values can be represented exactly. The discrepancy between the exact mathematical value and the stored/computed value is called the [[approximation error]].\n\n==Cybernetics==\nThe word ''[[cybernetics]]'' stems from the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] [[w:el:\u039a\u03c5\u03b2\u03b5\u03c1\u03bd\u03ae\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2|\u039a\u03c5\u03b2\u03b5\u03c1\u03bd\u03ae\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2]] (''kybern\u0113t\u0113s'', steersman, governor, pilot, or rudder \u2014 the same root as [[government]]). In applying corrections to the trajectory or course being steered cybernetics can be seen as the most general approach to error and its correction for the achievement of any goal. The term was suggested by [[Norbert Wiener]] to describe a new science of control and information in the animal and the machine. Wiener's early work was on [[noise]].\n\nThe cybernetician [[Gordon Pask]] held that the error that drives a [[servomechanism]] can be seen as a difference between a pair of analogous concepts in a servomechanism: the current state and the goal state. Later he suggested error can also be seen as an innovation or a contradiction depending on the context and perspective of interacting (observer) participants. The founder of [[management cybernetics]], \n[[Stafford Beer]], applied these ideas most notably in his [[viable system model]].\n\n==Biology==\n{{main|mutation}}\nIn [[biology]], an ''error'' is said to occur when perfect fidelity is lost in the copying of [[information]]. For example, in an asexually reproducing species, an error (or mutation) has occurred for each [[DNA]] [[nucleotide]] that differs between the [[child]] and the [[parent]]. Many of these mutations can be harmful, but unlike other types of errors, some are neutral or even beneficial. Mutations are an important force driving [[evolution]]. Mutations that make organisms more adapted to their [[environment (biophysical)|environment]] increase in the population through [[natural selection]] as organisms with favorable mutations have more [[offspring]].\n\n==Philately==\nIn [[philately]], an ''error'' refers to a [[postage stamp]] or piece of [[postal stationery]] that exhibits a printing or production mistake that differentiates it from a normal specimen or from the intended result. Examples are stamps printed in the wrong color or missing one or more colors, printed with a vignette [[Inverted Jenny|inverted]] in relation to its frame, produced without any perforations on one or more sides when the normal stamps are perforated, or printed on the wrong type of paper. Legitimate errors must always be produced and sold unintentionally. Such errors may or may not be scarce or rare. A ''[[Postage stamp design error|design error]]'' may refer to a mistake in the design of the stamp, such as a mislabeled subject, even if there are no printing or production mistakes.\n\n==Law==\n{{main|Error (law)}}\nIn [[Appeal|appellate review]], error typically refers to mistakes made by a [[trial court]] or some other court of first instance in applying the law in a particular [[legal case]].  This may involve such mistakes as improper admission of [[Evidence (law)|evidence]], inappropriate [[Jury instruction|instructions]] to the [[jury]], or applying the wrong [[Legal burden of proof|standard of proof]].\n\n== Stock market ==\n{{Main article|Fat-finger error}}\nA stock market error is a stock market transaction that was done due to an error, due to human [[failure]] or [[computer error]]s.\n\n==Governmental policy==\nWithin United States government intelligence agencies, such as [[Central Intelligence Agency]] agencies, ''error'' refers to ''intelligence error'', as previous assumptions that used to exist at a senior intelligence level within senior intelligence agencies, but has since been disproven, and is sometimes eventually listed as unclassified, and therefore more available to the [[General public|public]] and [[citizenry]] of the United States. The [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of information act]] provides American citizenry with a means to read intelligence reports that were mired in error. Per United States Central Intelligence Agency's website (as of August, 2008) intelligence error is described as:\n\n\"Intelligence errors are factual inaccuracies in analysis resulting from poor or missing data; intelligence failure is systemic organizational surprise resulting from incorrect, missing, discarded, or inadequate hypotheses.\"<ref>United States Central Intelligence Agency. [https://www.cia.gov/library/center-for-the-study-of-intelligence/csi-publications/books-and-monographs/analytic-culture-in-the-u-s-intelligence-community/chapter_1.htm Analytic Culture in the U.S. Intelligence Community]. Retrieved August 30, 2008.</ref>\n\n==Numismatics==\nIn [[numismatics]], an ''error'' refers to a [[coin]] or [[medal]] that has a minting mistake, similar to errors found in philately. Because the U.S. [[Mint (coin)|Bureau of the Mint]] keeps a careful eye on all potential errors, errors on U.S. coins are very few and usually very scarce. Examples of numismatic errors: extra metal attached to a coin, a clipped coin caused by the coin stamp machine stamping a second coin too early, double stamping of a coin. A coin that has been overdated, e.g.: 1942/41, is also considered an error.\n\n==See also==\n{{too many see alsos|date=June 2019}}\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Blooper]]\n* [[Blunder (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Error analysis (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Perfection]]\n* [[Popular errors]]\n* [[Refractive error]]\n* [[Trial and error]]\n* [[Margin of error]]\n* [[Medical error]]\n\n'''Psychology of error'''\n* [[Absent-mindedness]]\n* [[Lapsus]]\n\n'''Error in reasoning'''\n* [[Fallacy]]\n**[[Informal fallacy]]\n**[[Formal fallacy]]\n\n'''[[Error (linguistics)|Errors in language]]'''\n*[[Chinglish]]\n*[[Clerical error]]\n* [[Speech error]]\n* [[Typographical error]]\n*[[barbarism (linguistics)|Barbarism]]\n*[[Solecism]]\n\n'''Errors in science, technology'''\n* [[Custom error page]]\n* [[Divide by zero]]\n* [[Mathematical fallacy]]\n* [[Infinite loop]]\n* [[Stack overflow]]\n* [[Software bug]]\n\n'''Error diagnosis, correction and prevention'''\n* [[Error-correcting code memory]]\n* [[Error detection and correction]]\n* [[Error Detection and Handling]]\n* [[Forensic engineering]]\n* [[Root cause]]\n* [[Root cause analysis]]\n* [[Spell checking]]\n* [[Swiss cheese model]] of accident causation in human systems\n\n'''Production quality terminology'''\n* [[Nonconformity (quality)|Nonconformity]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{wiktionary}}\n* [http://www.accuracyproject.org/cbe-errors-books.html Errors contained in reference books \u2013 Internet Accuracy Project]\n\n[[Category:Error| ]]\n[[Category:Human communication]]\n[[Category:Measurement]]\n\n[[es:Error]]\n", "name_user": "Tech information seo", "label": "safe", "comment": "I can add one url", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Error"}
{"title_page": "Creaca", "text_new": "{{for|B\u00e2rza village in Mure\u0219 County, called Borza in Hungarian|S\u00e2nger}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = S\u0103laj\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in S\u0103laj County\n|official_name=Creaca\n|image_shield=\n|image_skyline=The rebuilt Praetorian gate (Porta Praetoria), Porolissum.jpg\n|image_caption=[[Porolissum]]\n|image_map              = Creaca jud Salaj.png\n|leader_name= Eugen Terec<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-06 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party=PSD\n|area_total_km2=74.16\n|elevation_max_m = 650\n|elevation_min_m = 200\n|coordinates              = {{coord|47|11|50|N|23|14|0|E|type:city_region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code              = 457096\n|area_code                = +40 260 and +40 360\n|website={{url|https://comunacreaca.ro/}}\n}}\n'''Creaca''' ({{lang-hu|Karika}}) is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] located in [[S\u0103laj County]], [[Romania]].\n\n==Villages==\nThe commune is composed of nine villages: Borza (''Egregyborzova''), Brebi (''Ber\u00e9d''), Brusturi (''Somr\u00f3\u00fajfalu''), Ciglean (''Csiglen''), Creaca, Jac (''Zs\u00e1kfalva''), Lupoaia (''Farkasmez\u0151''), Prod\u0103ne\u0219ti (''Prod\u00e1nfalva'') and Viile Jacului (''Sz\u00e1ll\u00e1ssz\u0151l\u0151hegy''). The largest village in terms of population and area is Jac, and the smallest is Viile Jacului.\n\n==History==\nIn the 1st century [[Anno Domini|AD]], [[Porolissum]], an ancient Roman city in [[Dacia]] was built on the western part of the commune. The city was the most north-eastern outpost of the [[Roman Empire]], and garrisoned 5,000 auxiliary soldiers transferred from [[Spain]], [[Gaul]], and [[Roman Britain|Britain]].\n\n==Demographics==\n\nAt the 2002 census, 97.8% of inhabitants were [[Romanians]] and 2.1% [[Roma in Romania|Roma]]. 71.1% were [[Romanian Orthodox]], 13.8% [[Baptist Union of Romania|Baptist]], 12.5% [[Pentecostal Union of Romania|Pentecostal]] and 2.1% stated they belonged to another religion.\n\n==Education==\nThere is a primary school (grades 1 to 8) in Creaca and Jac and only 1-4 grades in the rest of the villages, except Viile Jacului.\n\n==Occupations==\nThe main occupations involve the farms around the village. Most of the men are gone to work in other [[European Union]] countries. The ones who stayed work in [[Zal\u0103u]], commuting between Zal\u0103u and the commune's villages. In the [[Communist Romania|communist era]], the people worked mostly in Zal\u0103u and on state farms.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:TheViewofJac.JPG|View of Jac village\nFile:Marcus Traianus bust in Jac, Romania.jpg|Bust of [[Trajan]] in Jac\nFile:Jac biserica.JPG|Wooden Orthodox church in Jac\nFile:Old mine in Jac, Romania.JPG|Old mine in Jac\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://comunacreaca.ro/ Official site]\n\n{{S\u0103laj County}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in S\u0103laj County]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|B\u00e2rza village in Mure\u0219 County, called Borza in Hungarian|S\u00e2nger}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = S\u0103laj\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in S\u0103laj County\n|official_name=Creaca\n|image_shield=\n|image_skyline=The rebuilt Praetorian gate (Porta Praetoria), Porolissum.jpg\n|image_caption=[[Porolissum]]\n|image_map              = Creaca jud Salaj.png\n|leader_name=Terec Eugen|\n|leader_party=PDL\n|area_total_km2=74.16\n|elevation_max_m = 650\n|elevation_min_m = 200\n|coordinates              = {{coord|47|11|50|N|23|14|0|E|type:city_region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code              = 457096\n|area_code                = +40 260 and +40 360\n|website={{url|https://comunacreaca.ro/}}\n}}\n'''Creaca''' ({{lang-hu|Karika}}) is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] located in [[S\u0103laj County]], [[Romania]].\n\n==Villages==\nThe commune is composed of nine villages: Borza (''Egregyborzova''), Brebi (''Ber\u00e9d''), Brusturi (''Somr\u00f3\u00fajfalu''), Ciglean (''Csiglen''), Creaca, Jac (''Zs\u00e1kfalva''), Lupoaia (''Farkasmez\u0151''), Prod\u0103ne\u0219ti (''Prod\u00e1nfalva'') and Viile Jacului (''Sz\u00e1ll\u00e1ssz\u0151l\u0151hegy''). The largest village in terms of population and area is Jac, and the smallest is Viile Jacului.\n\n==History==\nIn the 1st century [[Anno Domini|AD]], [[Porolissum]], an ancient Roman city in [[Dacia]] was built on the western part of the commune. The city was the most north-eastern outpost of the [[Roman Empire]], and garrisoned 5,000 auxiliary soldiers transferred from [[Spain]], [[Gaul]], and [[Roman Britain|Britain]].\n\n==Demographics==\n\nAt the 2002 census, 97.8% of inhabitants were [[Romanians]] and 2.1% [[Roma in Romania|Roma]]. 71.1% were [[Romanian Orthodox]], 13.8% [[Baptist Union of Romania|Baptist]], 12.5% [[Pentecostal Union of Romania|Pentecostal]] and 2.1% stated they belonged to another religion.\n\n==Education==\nThere is a primary school (grades 1 to 8) in Creaca and Jac and only 1-4 grades in the rest of the villages, except Viile Jacului.\n\n==Occupations==\nThe main occupations involve the farms around the village. Most of the men are gone to work in other [[European Union]] countries. The ones who stayed work in [[Zal\u0103u]], commuting between Zal\u0103u and the commune's villages. In the [[Communist Romania|communist era]], the people worked mostly in Zal\u0103u and on state farms.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:TheViewofJac.JPG|View of Jac village\nFile:Marcus Traianus bust in Jac, Romania.jpg|Bust of [[Trajan]] in Jac\nFile:Jac biserica.JPG|Wooden Orthodox church in Jac\nFile:Old mine in Jac, Romania.JPG|Old mine in Jac\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://comunacreaca.ro/ Official site]\n\n{{S\u0103laj County}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in S\u0103laj County]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Creaca"}
{"title_page": "Gravity Noir", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Primary sources|date=November 2019}}\n{{Fanpov|date=February 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name = Gravity Noir\n|image = Gravity_Noir.jpg\n|caption = Original Gravity Noir bandmembers (from left): Peter Goos, Patrick Knight, Alex da Luz and Jorg Van der Heyden\n|background = group_or_band\n|origin = [[London]], England\n|genre = {{flatlist| \n* [[electronic dance music|EDM]]\n* [[Pop music|pop]]\n* [[reggae]]\n* [[ambient music|lounge]]\n* [[house music]]\n}}\n|years_active = 1990\u2013present\n|associated_acts = [[Greater Than One]]\n|label = {{flatlist|\n* [[Jumping Man Records]]\n* [[A Gravity Production]]\n* [[Indieplant]]\n* [[CD Baby]]\n}}\n|website = {{url|gravitynoir.com}}\n|current_members = Patrick Knight<br />Andrew Williams<br />Ambrosia Dash<br />\n|past_members = \n}}\n\n'''Gravity Noir''' is a British [[synth-pop]] band that was established in the early 1990s.\n\n==Background==\n\n[[File:Patrick & Bart Kaell.jpg|thumb|''Soundmixshow'' host [[Bart Ka\u00ebll]] and Patrick Knight as Boy George]]\nThe founder of Gravity Noir, British-Belgian [[Dual citizenship|dual citizen]] Patrick John Angele Knight,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hln.be/tag/patrick-knight/|title=Patrick Knight|last=Conaerts|first=Ben|date=15 August 2016|website=HLN|access-date=2019-08-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810101206/https://www.hln.be/tag/patrick-knight/|archive-date=10 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> performed as a [[Boy George]] tribute act and participated in several talent competitions between 1985 and 1996. In 1987 he was named among the top-12 best sound-mixers in Belgium by {{interlanguage link|Joepie|lt=''Joepie''|nl}} magazine, which released an album featuring Knight's cover of \"[[Everything I Own#Boy George version|Everything I Own]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rateyourmusic.com/release/comp/various_artists_f2/pieter_viking_presenteert_joepies_top_12_soundmix.p/|title=Pieter Viking presenteerd Joepie's top 12 soundmix|date=1987|website=rate your music|access-date=2019-10-10}}</ref> He won second and third place on Dutch television's ''[[Soundmixshow]]'' and also appeared on the British programme ''[[Stars in Their Eyes]]''. \n\n[[File:Greater Than One.jpg|thumb|Greater Than One (Patrick Knight at back with arms raised)]]\nWhile working on a side project called [[Greater Than One]] in 1991,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/artist/4B89AwyA8INUrw8MSZikB2/about|title=About GTO|date=1991|website=Spotify|access-date=2019-11-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107093142/https://open.spotify.com/artist/4B89AwyA8INUrw8MSZikB2/about|archive-date=2019-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/fr/song/b2462/GTO-Listen-To-The-Rhythm-Flow|title=GTO Listen to the rhythm flow|date=1991|website=Ultratop|access-date=2019-10-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113073131/https://www.ultratop.be/fr/song/b2462/GTO-Listen-To-The-Rhythm-Flow|archive-date=2019-11-13|url-status=live}}</ref> the name Gravity Noir was first used.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} Gravity Noir first performed as [[Culture Club]] on Belgian television channel [[VT4]] in July&nbsp;1996, hosted by Jo De Poorter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gravitynoir.com/videos_90s/|title=Patrick Knight as Boy George|last=4|first=VT|date=15 August 2016|website=Gravity Noir|access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref>\n\n== Early years ==\n[[File:Patrick Knight as Boy George.jpg|thumb|upright|Patrick Knight as Boy George]]\nGravity Noir was founded in Antwerp by Knight, the only permanent member of the group. Javier Rodriguez Iglesias, {{a.k.a.}} DJ Linetech, produced their first few songs before he was replaced by Peter Goos. The repertoire mainly consisted of 1980s covers. Dancers Alex da Luz and Jorg Van der Heyden completed the original band setup. The group briefly changed their name to Basics (B6), with the additions of female singer CJ and dancer Sofie. As B6, they recorded their first official music video for a remix that Goos made of the [[Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark]] hit \"[[Enola Gay (song)|Enola Gay]]\", which was broadcast on Belgian television channel [[FilmNet]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gravitynoir.com/videos_90s/|title=Gravity Noir - Enola Gay (B6 featuring Patrick Knight)|date=1997|website=Gravity Noir|access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref> The band continued to record demos in the late 1990s under their independent labels Jumping Man Records<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/label/46485-Jumping-Man-Records|title=Jumping Man Records Label|last=Records|first=Jumping Man|date=1991|website=Discogs|access-date=2019-09-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828032010/https://www.discogs.com/label/46485-Jumping-Man-Records|archive-date=2019-08-28|url-status=live}}</ref> and A Gravity Production.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/label/1092075-A-Gravity-Production/|title=A Gravity Production Label|last=Production|first=A Gravity|date=23 April 2011|website=Discogs|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190908035911/https://www.discogs.com/label/1092075-A-Gravity-Production|archive-date=8 September 2019|access-date=2019-08-06|url-status=live}}</ref> On 23 April 2011, a first official single called ''I've Got the Power'' was released, under the name of \"The Sisters of Divine Pleasure\", featuring Knight as [[drag queen]] Titless Strang\u00e9.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/3CK2ctdmagnuLWfFuQCALU?5=|title=I've got the power by Patrick Knight|date=23 April 2011|website=Spotify|access-date=2019-10-10}}</ref> In 2016, Knight decided to return to using the name Gravity Noir.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ascap.com/repertory#ace/search/performer/Gravity%20Noir/writer/Patrick%20Knight|title=ACE repertory|last=Gravity Noir|first=Patrick Knight|date=7 April 2016|website=ASCAP|access-date=2019-11-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127100731/https://www.ascap.com/repertory#ace/search/performer/Gravity%20Noir/writer/Patrick%20Knight|archive-date=27 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Later years and up to present days ==\n[[File:Gravity Noir - Andrew Williams (Band member).jpg|thumb|Andrew Williams]] \nGravity Noir sought to offer members the opportunity to showcase their individual talents and creativity.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} Andrew Williams joined the band in 2016 as a vocalist and wind instrumentalist, and to provide graphic designs.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} Williams is an artistic painter from [[Wakefield]] in [[West Yorkshire]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.painters-online.co.uk/artists/andreww16/|title=Andrew Williams|last=on line|first=Painters|date=3 September 2012|website=painters-online|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109115519/https://www.painters-online.co.uk/artists/andreww16/|archive-date=9 November 2019|access-date=2019-11-09|url-status=live}}</ref>{{relevance inline|date=March 2020}} Female lead singer Ambrosia Dash, who had lent her voice for Knight's solo projects, has sung several songs since Gravity Noir's comeback.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nAn official single and associated video clip called ''Mystery Knight''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://middeleeuwsterapel.nl/videoclip-gravity-noir/|title=Music Video Gravity Noir|last=Ter Apel|first=Middeleeuws|date=13 September 2016|website=Middeleeuws Ter Apel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723145134/https://middeleeuwsterapel.nl/videoclip-gravity-noir/|archive-date=23 July 2019|access-date=2019-07-23|url-status=live}}</ref> was released by Gravity Noir on 7&nbsp;April 2016. It was recorded at [[Ter Apel Monastery]] in the Netherlands during the annual Ter Apel mediaeval festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://allexciting.com/medieval-festival-middeleeuws-ter-apel/|title=Medieval Festival in Ter Apel|last=Festival Ter Apel|first=Medieval|date=13 September 2016|website=Allexciting|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006090327/http://allexciting.com/medieval-festival-middeleeuws-ter-apel/|archive-date=6 October 2019|access-date=2019-10-05|url-status=live}}</ref> Three albums have been released so far: ''The Early Years'', ''Handmade'' and ''Liberation''. The last of these generated two {{abbr|No.|number}}&nbsp;1 hits in the UK N1M EDM ([[electronic dance music]]) charts: \"Open Your Mind\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.numberonemusic.com/charts?country_id=224&filter_action=1&genre_id=95&geo=national&query=open%20your%20mind%20gravity%20noir|title=Open your mind|last=Music|first=Number One|date=2017|website=N1M Charts|archive-url=http://www.numberonemusic.com/charts?country_id=224&filter_action=1&genre_id=95&geo=national&query=open%20your%20mind%20gravity%20noir|archive-date=2017|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref> and \"Avalon L.A.\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.numberonemusic.com/charts?country_id=224&filter_action=1&genre_id=95&geo=national&query=avalon%20L.A.%20gravity%20noir|title=Avalon L.A.|last=Music|first=Number One|date=2017|website=N1M Charts|archive-url=http://www.numberonemusic.com/charts?country_id=224&filter_action=1&genre_id=95&geo=national&query=avalon%20L.A.%20gravity%20noir|archive-date=2017|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the band began working on ''Future Days'' for an anticipated release in 2020 and was released on 18 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/be/album/future-days/1489030385?l=en|title=Future Days by Gravity Noir|last=Music|first=Apple|date=2020-03-18|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> The single \"Flying High\" was officially released on 22&nbsp;March 2019. Two successors were released. One with the title \"Planet Called Love\" during the summer of 2019 and the second one \"Universal Party (Supernatural)\" was released on Valentine's Day 2020.\n\nDue to Knight's life-threatening heart condition, [[Brugada syndrome]], it is no longer possible for him to perform live, and the band is seeking a new lead singer. Knight continues to compose and produce all music for Gravity Noir. He has reworked the track \"The Thrifty Wife & the Kite\" by the folk and ceilidh dance band [[Banjax]] into a Gravity Noir remix. A special Christmas edition was released in November&nbsp;2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.cdbaby.com/cd/banjax|title=Banjax & Gravity Noir|last=The thrifty wife|first=& the kite|date=22 November 2019|website=CD Baby Music|archive-url=https://store.cdbaby.com/cd/banjax|archive-date=22 November 2019|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref> The original track was written by Knight's cousin Keith Leech in 1992.\n\n== Charity ==\nGravity Noir recorded the single ''Another Dimension (Dementia)'' and accompanying video for the benefit of the Alzheimer League Flanders and [[Alzheimer's Society]] United Kingdom. The presentation was supported and attended by the published press<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hln.be/in-de-buurt/hoboken/-meest-persoonlijke-lied-ooit~a6b51381/|title=Most personal song ever|last=Conaerts|first=Ben|date=15 August 2016|website=HLN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723145130/https://www.hln.be/in-de-buurt/hoboken/-meest-persoonlijke-lied-ooit~a6b51381/|archive-date=23 July 2019|access-date=2019-05-01|url-status=live}}</ref> and covered by Belgium newspapers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gravitynoir.com/press/|title=Published Press|last=De Beuckeleer|first=Koen|date=12 August 2016|website=Gravity Noir|access-date=2019-10-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927124803/http://gravitynoir.com/press/|archive-date=27 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://putte.bibliotheek.be/krantenarchief?q=%22Gravity%20Noir%22|title=Song about dementia|last=Streekkrant|first=De|date=14 September 2016|website=Library Putte & Beerzel|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://putte.bibliotheek.be/krantenarchief?q=%22Gravity%20Noir%22|title=Most personal song ever|last=Conaerts|first=Ben|date=18 August 2016|website=Library Putte & Beerzel|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://putte.bibliotheek.be/krantenarchief?q=%22Gravity%20Noir%22|title=Singer and songwriter from Hoboken made a single for the Alzheimer's Society|last=De Beuckeleer|first=Koen|date=12 August 2016|website=Library Putte & Beerzel|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://putte.bibliotheek.be/krantenarchief?q=%22Gravity%20Noir%22|title=Especially for mum|last=De Beuckeleer|first=Koen|date=12 August 2016|website=Library Putte & Beerzel|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> At the beginning of 2017, Gravity Noir released the single and video for \"Much Too Soon to Say Goodbye\" to raise discussion around the issues of suicide. In September 2018, they released the single and video for \"Open Your Mind\" (The Future is Ours Remix). For this track, they found the support and help from film director Lubomir Arsov,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3396016/|title=Lubomir Arsov|access-date=2019-08-06|website=IMDB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217175914/http://www.imdb.com/name/nm3396016/|archive-date=2017-02-17|url-status=live}}</ref> who provided images from his 2017 short film ''In-shadow: A Modern Odyssey''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7ODB-G6SghE|title=Gravity Noir - Open your mind(The Lubomir Arsov tribute)(The future is ours remix))|access-date=2019-08-06|website=YOUTUBE|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407053513/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7ODB-G6SghE|archive-date=2019-04-07|url-status=live}}</ref> The theme of this project revolves around the many prejudices of psychological problems and bullying behaviour.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Bandmembers ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Kenny Patrick Cogen and Suzanne Vuegen (Band members Gravity Noir).jpg|thumb|Kenny Patrick Cogen and Suzanne Vuegen]]\n* Patrick Knight \u2013 producer, main and backing vocals, bongos, electronic sounds (1990\u2013present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ascap.com/repertory#ace/performer/GRAVITY%20NOIR|title=ACE Repertory|website=www.ascap.com|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://www.ascap.com/repertory#ace/performer/GRAVITY%20NOIR|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|title=Gravity Noir Official Website|website=www.gravitynoir.com|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Javier Rodriguez Iglesias (DJ Linetech) \u2013 synthesizers, keyboards, electronic sounds (1990\u20131996, 2016\u20132019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ascap.com/repertory#ace/search/performer/Gravity%20Noir/title/Into%20a%20new%20world%20(DJ%20Linetech%20candy%20remix)|title=ACE Repertory|website=www.ascap.com|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://www.ascap.com/repertory#ace/search/performer/Gravity%20Noir/title/Into%20a%20new%20world%20(DJ%20Linetech%20candy%20remix)|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|title=Gravity Noir Official Website|website=www.gravitynoir.com|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Peter Goos \u2013 synthesizers, keyboards (1996\u20131998)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ascap.com/repertory#ace/search/performer/Gravity%20Noir/title/I%27ve%20got%20the%20power|title=ACE Repertory|website=www.ascap.com|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://www.ascap.com/repertory#ace/search/performer/Gravity%20Noir/title/I%27ve%20got%20the%20power|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|title=Gravity Noir Official Website|website=www.gravitynoir.com|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Ambrosia Dash \u2013 main vocals, backing vocals (1990\u20131993, 2016\u2013present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|title=Gravity Noir Official Website|website=www.gravitynoir.com|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Charles Temmerman \u2013 backing vocals (1990\u20131993)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|title=Gravity Noir Official Website|website=www.gravitynoir.com|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Alex da Luz \u2013 dancer (1996\u20132012)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|title=Gravity Noir Official Website|website=www.gravitynoir.com|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Jorg Van der Heyden \u2013 dancer, graphic designer (1996\u20132019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|title=Gravity Noir Official Website|website=www.gravitynoir.com|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* C.J. \u2013 main vocals, backing vocals, dancer (1996\u20131997)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|title=Gravity Noir Official Website|website=www.gravitynoir.com|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Sofie \u2013 dancer (1996\u20131997)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|title=Gravity Noir Official Website|website=www.gravitynoir.com|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Andrew Williams \u2013 main vocals, backing vocals, wind instruments, graphic designer (2016\u2013present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jaxsta.com/recording/04144f94-c2ee-4b7b-a644-f38f20886444/overview|title=Open Your Mind (feat. Andrew Williams)|website=www.jaxsta.com|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://jaxsta.com/recording/04144f94-c2ee-4b7b-a644-f38f20886444/overview|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|title=Gravity Noir Official Website|website=www.gravitynoir.com|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Kenny Patrick Cogen \u2013 dancer (2016\u2013present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|title=Gravity Noir Official Website|website=www.gravitynoir.com|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Suzanne Vuegen \u2013 dancer (2016\u2013present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|title=Gravity Noir Official Website|website=www.gravitynoir.com|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://gravitynoir.com/bandmembers|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n; Albums\n\n* ''The Early Years''  2016  (CD Baby/Gravity Productions UPC 191061029427)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gravitynoir.com/dashboard/pages/videos_90s|title=Gravity Noir The early years|last=Gravity|first=Noir|date=2015-11-10|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref>\n* ''Handmade''  2016  (CD Baby/Indieplant/Gravity Productions UPC 0680596923527)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7BRUG7fgQfA&list=OLAK5uy_kGxBjMk__4DeDCTrnNz1qI0LTEpjXNz7M|title=Gravity Noir Handmade|last=Topic|first=YouTube|date=2016-11-30|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/gravity-noir-mn0003626360|title=Gravity Noir|last=AllMusic|first=Discography|date=2016-11-30|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110093113/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/gravity-noir-mn000